					<item>
				<guid>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-1197130#post-2421980</guid>
				<title>(no title)</title>
				<link>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-1197130/scp-2991#post-2421980</link>
				<description></description>
				<pubDate>Sat, 12 Dec 2015 05:03:07 +0000</pubDate>
				<wikidot:authorName>Hercules Rockefeller</wikidot:authorName>				<wikidot:authorUserId>2314402</wikidot:authorUserId>				<content:encoded>
					<![CDATA[
						 <p>I enjoyed this a lot more than I thought I would&#8230;<br /> +1</p> <div class="collapsible-block"> <div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">Small&nbsp;nitpicks/possible&nbsp;mistakes</a></div> <div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none"> <div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">Hide</a></div> <div class="collapsible-block-content"> <p>There are two instances of &quot;SCP-2991 is additionally capable of&quot; within the same paragraph (2nd paragraph of the description). While there is nothing inherently wrong with that, you might be better off rephrasing one of the instances.</p> <blockquote> <p>SCP-2991 has recently been observed communicating with researchers in the past few months by rolling its length to become thinner</p> </blockquote> <p>I would replace &quot;rolling its length&quot; by &quot;rolling itself along its width&quot; to make it clearer what you mean, and to make the sentence less 'iffy' grammatically, as I'm pretty sure something can't &quot;roll its length&quot;; also, &quot;length&quot; is used here to mean &quot;lengthwise&quot;, which is defined as &quot;in a direction parallel with a thing's length&quot;, which is the opposite of what you meant to describe, hence my suggestion of replacing it with &quot;along its width&quot;.</p> <p>Again, though, great job!</p> </div> </div> </div> 
				 	]]>
				</content:encoded>							</item>
